Prints what the loader hands the kernel on `-machine q35`, before any of the
Stage 2.2 code trusts it: the RSDP pointer, and every firmware memory region
with its kind. The question it answers is whether the ECAM window QEMU places
at 0xb000_0000 appears in the firmware map as a reserved region — in which case
`Inventory::device` refuses it and the typed-window path needs a different
rule — or as a hole, which is what `Kind::Device` requires.

Apply with `git apply experiments/x86_64-firmware-report.patch`, run
`cargo smoke x86_64`, then revert.

--- a/crates/platforms/x86_64/src/lib.rs
+++ b/crates/platforms/x86_64/src/lib.rs
@@ pub fn start
     let memory_map = BootloaderMemoryMap::new(&raw.memory_regions);
+    emergency_write("MOLT_RSDP: ");
+    emergency_hex(raw.rsdp_addr.into_option().unwrap_or(0));
+    emergency_write("\n");
+    for region in raw.memory_regions.iter() {
+        emergency_write("MOLT_REGION: ");
+        emergency_hex(region.start);
+        emergency_write(" ");
+        emergency_hex(region.end);
+        emergency_write(" ");
+        emergency_hex(match region.kind {
+            BootMemoryRegionKind::Usable => 0,
+            BootMemoryRegionKind::Bootloader => 1,
+            BootMemoryRegionKind::UnknownUefi(tag) | BootMemoryRegionKind::UnknownBios(tag) => {
+                0x1000 + tag as u64
+            }
+            _ => 2,
+        });
+        emergency_write("\n");
+    }
